events.summary: Johann Sebastian Bach burst onto the scene in Eisenach, making it a family affair with eight siblings. His father was the town's music chief, ensuring Bach had an early start on the 'Soundtrack of Life'.
At the tender age of 10, Bach became an orphan, marking the beginning of his epic quest to master music. Living with his elder brother, he learned to sneak in some music lessons on the sly.
Bach enrolled in the prestigious St. Michael's School in Lüneburg. Here, he played the organ while trying not to trip over aristocrat’s egos—a true test of character!
Bach landed a gig as court musician in Weimar. Despite dubious duties, his stellar keyboard skills made him a local celebrity, turning 'sitting in the back' into a major role.
Taking a break from the royal antics, Bach became the organist at the New Church in Arnstadt. He was invited to give a swanky inaugural recital that turned into a mini-concert festival!
Bach tied the knot with his second cousin Maria Barbara, turning family reunions into duet practices. Who knew family trees had such harmonious branches?
After a brief marriage honeymoon, he returned to Weimar as the court's official music director. The only thing more challenging than his compositions was his growing family!
Bach was promoted to Konzertmeister, meaning he had to compose a church cantata every month. Talk about turning the pressure up—I mean, who wouldn’t thrive under a deadline like that?
After a fallout with the authorities, Bach spent almost a month in jail before getting a rather rude dismissal from Weimar. Turns out his stubbornness was an occupational hazard!
Bach took the gig as Kapellmeister in Köthen, a place where his style thrived. He finally got to focus on composing without the church's weekly playlists getting in the way!
In Leipzig, Bach took on the role of Thomaskantor. Not only did this give him legitimacy, it also came with the task of composing for the city’s main Lutheran churches—talk about being in demand!

Bach was granted the title of court composer by Augustus III, which probably did wonders for his street cred. It’s as if the universe officially recognized him as 'Bach, the composer of epic proportions.'
Bach passed away after a botched eye surgery. His final act was possibly composing music for heaven's gate; we can only imagine the celestial concert that followed!

Bach earned the title of Kapellmeister, and it turned out to be a sweet gig thanks to Prince Leopold, who thought Bach was as fabulous as a baroque wig. Most of his work during this time was secular since the prince preferred foot-tapping tunes over solemn hymns.

After the unfortunate passing of his first wife, Bach struck gold with Anna Magdalena, a soprano who brightened his life like a new pair of boots! They tied the knot and had a whole troupe of 13 kids, giving the term 'musical family' a whole new meaning.

Bach bagged the prestigious role of Thomaskantor, where he was tasked with directing church music and keeping the St. Thomas School students in line while belting out cantatas. It was like being the head chef at a restaurant where the main course was church music!
He debuted his first cantata, 'Die Elenden sollen essen,' with all the flair of a director unveiling a blockbuster! Who knew church music could have such a dramatic debut?

In a move that was both savvy and musical, Bach snagged the directorship of the Collegium Musicum, bringing his flair for composition to the coffeehouses, effectively making coffee breaks a lot more melodic.

events.event: Composition of the Mass in B minor
events.summary: Bach undertook the grand task of composing his Mass in B minor—a fine work that combined all the glory of his earlier compositions into a symphonic stew that would have everyone in heaven humming along!

events.event: Final preparations for The Art of Fugue
events.summary: Bach immersed himself in the creation of 'The Art of Fugue,' a complex web of counterpoint ready to make even the greatest musicians dizzy. It was his grand finale, like the last act of a long-running play!

From a young age, Bach was busy soaking up the musical genius of his Baroque buddies like Vivaldi and Handel. He studied their works like a sponge in a pool of notes, ensuring he wouldn’t just dip his toes in, but dive headfirst into creativity!

Bach became a big cheese in the music scene when he took on the role of Thomaskantor, where he not only composed but also taught the church’s small catechism. Talk about multitasking - music and theology all under one roof!

In a true showman fashion, Bach jazzed up Pergolesi's Stabat Mater by rearranging it and adding some pizzazz with the viola. Let’s be honest, who wouldn’t want their music to go from ‘meh’ to ‘marvelous’?

events.event: Capriccio on the Departure of a Beloved Brother
events.summary: Bach penned this affectionate piece, showcasing his flair for modulation like a magician pulls rabbits from hats. He was already pushing tonal boundaries while others were still figuring out how to place their fingers on the keys!

Bach dropped a musical bombshell with the release of The Well-Tempered Clavier, proving he had the keys to success—literally! With two volumes, he displayed mastery across all keys and gave the music world the gift of 'Hey, I can play in any key!'

Bach took a casual stroll down the path of counterpoint and decided to build a mansion there. His meticulous fugues were the crème de la crème—a musical cat’s cradle of intertwining melodies that left listeners both awe-struck and slightly dizzy.

At a young age, he snagged the gig of court musician in Weimar, proving that small-town musicians can indeed move up the ladder of musical society, even if it involved long hours and occasionally dodging the court jester.

Bach took on the prestigious title of Thomaskantor in Leipzig, marking the beginning of his weekly minor miracle—writing and performing a new cantata every Sunday. It was like composing the weekly newsletter, but way more melodious!

Although he was revered as an exceptional organist, it was during this period that Bach's genius as a composer began to receive wider recognition. Who would have thought that blending melodies could lead to such acclaim?

Bach tackled his magnum opus, the Mass in B minor. It was his grand musical farewell, a composition so elaborate and complex it probably had its own fan club. It wasn't performed in full during his lifetime, but it surely was the talk of the town!
Bach earned the esteemed title of court composer from Augustus III of Poland, making his life sound fancier than it likely was! Who knew composing could lead to snazzy titles and courtly drama?

Bach penned The Well-Tempered Clavier, a masterpiece to teach the world that you could indeed play in all keys without bursting into flames. He set the stage for keyboardists everywhere to show off their tuning skills!
In a bid for employment, Bach composed the Brandenburg Concertos and sent them off to a Margrave, but sadly it was a no-go. At least he got to be a ‘concerto grosso’ for the ages!

After honing his craft, Bach snagged his first big gig as an organist in Arnstadt. He probably came in with a confidence that suggested he was the Mozart of his time, and while he may not have created any viral hits, he got the local folks tapping their feet.

Bach unleashed a flurry of cantatas during his time in Leipzig. If Robert Frost had written about musical compositions, he might have said that the road less traveled was paved with Bach’s shoes, and often led to a church or two.

How does one wrap up a musical career? With a masterpiece, of course! Bach began working on 'The Art of Fugue', a project so complex that it's as if he was trying to show off to the universe. That'll teach those stars to shine brighter than him!

Bach took his final bow in this world, leaving behind an impressive legacy. It’s said he left the stage not with a whimper, but with a symphonic flourish, convincing everyone that he might just be taking a long intermission.

Bach tied the knot for the first time, proving that behind every great composer there is often a spouse who graciously tolerates late-night practice sessions and endless conversations about harmonies.

Bach was appointed court composer, a position that came with the perks of having his own orchestra—although he quickly learned that composing for royalty was like trying to please a cat: no matter what you do, it’s never enough.
After his first wife's untimely departure, Bach found love once more, showing that true devotion can lead to new beginnings and a few more children to add to the family's musical legacy.

Bach released 'The Well-Tempered Clavier', a collection that ensured every pianist would have a reason to practice scales for centuries to come. It was said to be a genius way of turning scales into a fashionable topic at cocktail parties.

events.event: Completion of the Mass in B Minor
events.summary: After years of composing, Bach finally put the finishing touches on the Mass in B Minor. It was a musical feast that left everyone wondering if he had secretly enlisted a heavenly choir for inspiration.

In 1703, young Bach took up his first official position as an organist in Arnstadt. It was a gig filled with plenty of keyboard antics—who knew he’d be setting the bar for future organists while having the time of his life in the dusty church?

In 1707, Bach tied the knot with his second cousin, Maria Barbara, which was undoubtedly a beautiful union of musical minds and a family tie that would linger like a well-composed cadence. This match brought him joy and inspiration, not to mention a growing brood!

By 1708, Bach was appointed court composer in Weimar. He had the sweet job title, along with the not-so-sweet task of managing the Duke's musical whims. But let's face it, who wouldn’t want to produce music for royalty while they grind out masterpieces?

In 1723, Bach became the Cantor at St. Thomas Church in Leipzig, which is where he really found his groove. His job was to teach and compose choral music, which meant he was like the ultimate musical coach—whipping up choirs and giving them the tools to sound fabulous!

In 1729, Bach completed his masterwork, the St. Matthew Passion, which had such emotional depth that it left listeners torn between bliss and tears. Seriously, it was like a musical rollercoaster that didn’t stop for breath until the very last note!
